1529755200.0} {"text": "Definicja \"≈õredniaka\"? Ca≈Ça para posz≈Ça w, hmm, uczucia? ZaczynajƒÖc ju≈º od pierwszych zapowiedzi. Nadal pamiƒôtam zestresowanego go≈õcia z w≈Ç√≥czkowym przyjacielem w ≈Çapach podczas konferencji. Gra dzia≈Ça na wyobra≈∫niƒô i stara siƒô dotykaƒá tych czu≈Çych fragment√≥w w naszej g≈Çowie. Przyjemna muzyka i PIƒòKNA grafika. Do oprawy wizualnej nie mo≈ºna siƒô przyczepiƒá. Tutaj robotƒô wykonano fenomenalnƒÖ. A co do historii... Tu mam problem. M√≥g≈Çbym jƒÖ stre≈õciƒá w trzech s≈Çowach: \"ludzie siƒô starzejƒÖ\". Wiele tu nie ma. Naprawdƒô nie wƒÖtpiƒô, ≈ºe to, co tu jest, niekt√≥rym wystarczy. Mo≈ºe kogo≈õ oczaruje ten klimat. Ewidentnie nie by≈Ç tworzony z my≈õlƒÖ o mnie. Nie ma tu nic wyjƒÖtkowego, to sƒÖ proste rzeczy. A mo≈ºe akurat kto≈õ jest w takim momencie w ≈ºyciu, ≈ºe go to autentycznie wzruszy. Nie wszystko musi byƒá \"odkrywcze\", byle na kogo≈õ dzia≈Ça≈Ço. Tu siƒô jednak pojawia pewien problem: gameplay. Bo jak my≈õlƒô o tym, do kogo jest kierowana ta gra, powinna byƒá raczej przyjemna w obs≈Çudze i niezbyt trudna. A jednak potrafi wkurzyƒá. G≈Ç√≥wny patent, czyli jeste≈õmy ograniczeni w≈Ç√≥czkƒÖ i musimy szukaƒá materia≈Çu, by dostaƒá siƒô dalej, jest OK. Jednak nie wszystko tu dzia≈Ça jak powinno. ≈Åapanie siƒô w≈Ç√≥czkƒÖ element√≥w wydaje siƒô niekonsekwentne, przez co zdarza siƒô spadaƒá i trzeba powtarzaƒá akcje wiele razy. Fizyka te≈º czasem wariuje. Nasza niƒá mo≈ºe spa≈õƒá pod obiekt i pozostanie restart, bo siƒô zablokujemy (zdarzy≈Ço mi siƒô na drzewie). Raz musia≈Çem rozwiƒÖzaƒá sieƒá, bo element, kt√≥ry chcia≈Çem po niej wturlaƒá, przeszed≈Ç przez niƒÖ do po≈Çowy i zawisnƒÖ≈Ç jak koralik. A nawet kiedy wszystko dzia≈Ça dobrze, mo≈ºe byƒá zwyczajnie za ciƒô≈ºko. Jak siƒô gdzie≈õ utknie, najlepiej spr√≥bowaƒá popychaƒá r√≥≈ºne elementy, bo czƒôsto trudno zauwa≈ºyƒá, ≈ºe co≈õ jest do ruszenia. A ostatni poziom... Zagadka z latarniƒÖ nie jest skomplikowana, ale wymaga trochƒô zrƒôczno≈õci i szybkiego reagowania. Nic wcze≈õniej w grze nie stawia≈Ço takiego wyzwania. Bardzo irytujƒÖcy moment, zostawiajƒÖcy gorzki posmak, bo po nim jest ju≈º niewiele. Dla kogo to jest? Jak kto≈õ chce siƒô zwyczajnie odprƒô≈ºyƒá, mo≈ºe siƒô wkurzyƒá przy platformowaniu. Jak komu≈õ zale≈ºy na wyzwaniu, bƒôdzie ziewaƒá przez d≈Çu≈ºyzny. SƒÖdzƒÖc po wielu pozytywnych opiniach, jednak do wielu ta produkcja trafi≈Ça. Wiƒôc sam oceniam \"na plus\", choƒá tak minimalnie. Trudno mi jednoznacznie poleciƒá, ale skoro to uko≈Ñczy≈Çem mimo wszystko, na pewno nie jest \"z≈Çe\".", "appid": "1225560", "steamid": "profiles/76561198023154119", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "2", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1597579200.0} {"text": "Addicting and fun", "appid": "751780", "steamid": "profiles/76561198122163841", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": 0, "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1575115200.0} {"text": "Whatever floats your boat. Raft is an Early Access survival game developed by Redbeet Interactive. You begin with a tiny raft and over the course of the game you‚Äôll collect flotsam for resources to help you expand your raft and make surviving just a little easier. Along the way, you‚Äôll run into islands to stop at as well as stave off an incredibly obsessive shark. One thing I will say, is this game can feel a little bit monotonous. I strangely enjoy monotony at times, but if you don‚Äôt then this game might not offer enough to keep you interested. Positives: Raft has fairly good visuals, nothing groundbreaking but it‚Äôs certainly nice to look at (I particularly like the sunrises and sunsets). The core gameplay is fairly simple, but surprisingly well done. The meat of the game is really just using a grappling hook to pull in floating resources which you then use to make different tools and equipment to help you survive, such as water purifiers and wooden spears. It can feel a little slow at times, but for the most part it felt like there was a decent level of progression in the game. As well as fishing for resources (and fish) there are also islands that you sometimes come across. Each island has something unique about it, but they all contain some of the rarer resources required for more advanced crafting. The islands help break things up a bit and add some nice variety to the game, though they can be a little bit too challenging to get on. You also come across abandoned rafts every one in a while that also add some nice variety. The difficulty level you choose makes a surprisingly significant impact on how the game feels. The easy mode is very relaxing, little pressure from the survival elements, and you can take the game at your own pace. Normal mode requires more attention to be paid to how hungry and thirsty you are, and things can pretty quickly get away from you. The hardest mode obviously offers the most challenge but honestly it also has the least realism since you‚Äôre constantly needing to top up your survival bars. There‚Äôs also a creative mode, that‚Äôs pretty self-explanatory. Playing singleplayer and multiplayer also offer two very different experiences. Singleplayer makes you feel lonely and isolated. It‚Äôs also more relaxing and I actually found it quite meditative too. Multiplayer (depending on who you‚Äôre playing with of course) is a bit more involved and energetic, progression is a bit faster too. I‚Äôve enjoyed playing both, but I think I prefer singleplayer for this one. In a sea (ha, get it) of survival games, Raft actually manages to have a pretty unique Neutral: For the main antagonist of a game, the shark is a little underwhelming. I actually ended up turning off shark attacks while I was playing because I enjoyed it more. The shark really just attacks you when you‚Äôre in the water and every so often it‚Äôll attack your Raft and try to break some off. It definitely adds some extra challenge; I just didn‚Äôt particularly enjoy that challenge. This really comes down to personal preference though. The survival requirements can be a little intense, but changing the difficulty level really makes a difference. I figure some people will probably be annoyed that the main challenge comes from how quickly your hunger and thirst bars decrease, but I personally didn‚Äôt mind just making the game easier overall to enjoy the game more. Negatives: I really wish there was more music in the game. There were long stretches of time where the game was pretty much completely quiet. I‚Äôm sure there are plenty of people who play with their own music or podcasts, but I found the in-game music added to the immersion when it was actually playing. While I do enjoy some of the monotony, I do still feel like the game can be a little too repetitive. I often went long periods between seeing an island, and it can get pretty uninteresting if you‚Äôre an hour or two into just floating around looking at nothing but ocean. I don‚Äôt think there‚Äôs enough wood to go around. Planks are the main resource used in construction and crafting, and if you‚Äôre trying to build a decent sized raft then you need a LOT of planks. I got kind of fed up of building one new piece of my raft, going back and spending a few minutes getting more planks, and then repeating that again and again until I had built up what I wanted. Verdict: Raft ends up being a little too repetitive even for someone who enjoys monotony but it‚Äôs a fairly unique survival game and you can customize your experience with it fairly well. I‚Äôd certainly recommend it for fans of the survival genre.", "appid": "648800", "steamid": "profiles/76561198451403640", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "2", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": true, "tstamp_created": 1561809600.0} {"text": ";lbncfglvhn", "appid": "1281930", "steamid": "profiles/76561198121830548", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": 0, "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1591099200.0} {"text": "N√£o estou conseguindo entrar sera que vou perder tudo algu√©m me ajuda!