_up": "2", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1483790400.0} {"text": "GOOD^^", "appid": "711810", "steamid": "profiles/76561198453366444", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "3", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1591876800.0} {"text": "Golden Frieza died to a weak Vegeta while he was stuck in a rock trying to revive me 10/10 best AI 2015", "appid": "323470", "steamid": "profiles/76561198062243613", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "3", "votes_funny": "9", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1437307200.0} {"text": "–æ—á–µ–Ω—å –∫–ª–∞—Å—Å–Ω–∞—è –∏–≥—Ä–∞. –∏–Ω—Ç–µ—Ä–µ—Å–Ω–æ –∏–≥—Ä–∞—Ç—å —Å –¥—Ä—É–∑—å—è–º–∏. —Ö–æ—Ä–æ—à–∞—è –≥—Ä–∞—Ñ–∏–∫–∞ –∏ –≥–µ–π–º–ø–ª–µ–π", "appid": "218620", "steamid": "profiles/76561198299108348", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": 0, "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1593518400.0} {"text": ".", "appid": "230410", "steamid": "profiles/76561198042811996", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": 0, "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1542801600.0} {"text": "I am only what I believe to be halfway through the game. Camera angles can be a bit of a troll at times but all in all it seems to be a very good game with a great cheesy sci-fi story. The narrator is the \"director\" and he is a riot which makes it all the better! 8/10 (so far.. would be higher if it cost less for how short its starting to seem and the camera angles are trolly.)", "appid": "353700", "steamid": "profiles/76561198271126833", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "1", "votes_funny": "20", "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1478865600.0} {"text": "If you enjoyed searching for Waldo, you're going to enjoy this game. However, there is no easily identifiable character like Waldo; instead, each area has a list of people or things to find. At first some are daunting, both due to the size of the areas and due to the size of the items (golf ball, for example). However, each item to find comes with a clue and the clue points to a bigger thing to search for. For example, one item to find is a mushroom and the clue is that a pig is about to sniff it out. So instead of looking for a little mushroom, you can look for a much bigger hog. In fact, I was never stuck on an area due to the smallest items, and the couple times I did get stuck a little, I just wasn't seeing what was right in front of me. In fact, in addition to the verbal clues, there are auditory clues. I didn't discover this until the last few areas when I heard someone crying out in distress and looked for the source of the sound, but it's a nice feature. There are two really unique aspects to the game that add oodles of charm. First, the game sounds are all done with the human mouth. Some are definitely more effective than others. I think the birds flying away sound is pretty weak, but I'll never get tired of the alligators or vultures or garage doors. That's the second unique aspect - you can manipulate the environment and, in fact, you need to in order to find things. For example, opening doors or flipping switches or moving clouds out of the way or cutting bushes. It's so much fun! Each area feels unique even when it has the same unifying theme - like the factory. There is a nice variety - some areas are small, some are huge, some are puzzles. My personal favorite is the desert, because this game also has a great sense of humor. For example, in the city there is a boss lady at the top of a skyscraper surrounded by bags with dollar signs on them. That made me laugh. I thought the factory was going to be boring, but it wasn't at all. Best of all, once you complete the game, you get a message that the devs are going to continue to add more areas. They added the factory areas about 4 months after they released the game. I'm definitely looking forward to more. I have only two little criticisms. Not everything you can click on makes a unique sound. Lots of things do, but I'd love it if EVERYTHING did. Secondly, at one point you're supposed to look for a sunbathing turtle that only vaguely resembles a turtle. Small price to pay, in my opinion, for the quirky hand drawn art style, and that's the only instance I came across. As for replay value, you can reset your progress. You also don't have to find everything in an area before being able to move on - just a certain number. However, it is like Waldo in the sense that once you know where something is, you know where it is. But so much time and care was put into making each area a cohesive whole with objects to find spread throughout in a way that encourages the player to scan and enjoy the entire area, that I wouldn't trade that for any sort of randomization. Even if you only play through this game once, I think it's well worth the full price. Personally, I love it so much, I'm sure I'll be back and I will instabuy anything else put out by this dev. With so many slapped-together-to-make-a-quick-buck games on Steam, I definitely appreciate ones like this that are full of detail and heart. I find myself smiling about parts of the game much later - like the ghost mail or those silly monkeys. That's a rare find. UPDATE - As promised, devs just added new snow areas. Thank you!", "appid": "435400", "steamid": "profiles/76561198039619705", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "38", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1511956800.0} {"text": "Its too fun.. can't stop playing! Get Terraria now! With constant updates, this game will keep you playing for a long time.", "appid": "105600", "steamid": "profiles/76561198076482906", "voted_up": true, "votes_up": "1", "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1383480000.0} {"text": "‚ñà‚ñÄ‚ñÄ„Ö§ ‚ñà „Ö§ ‚ñà„Ö§ ‚ñà„Ö§ ‚ñà„Ö§‚ñÄ‚ñÄ‚ñà‚ñÄ‚ñÄ„Ö§„Ö§‚ñà„Ö§ ‚ñà„Ö§ ‚ñà‚ñÄ‚ñÄ‚ñÑ „ÄÄ ‚ñÄ‚ñÄ‚ñà„Ö§‚ñà‚ñÄ‚ñÄ‚ñà„Ö§ ‚ñà„Ö§ ‚ñà„Ö§ „Ö§ ‚ñà„Ö§„Ö§„Ö§ ‚ñà „Ö§ ‚ñà„Ö§ ‚ñà „Ö§ ‚ñà „ÄÄ ‚ñÄ‚ñÄ‚ñÄ„Ö§‚ñÄ „Ö§‚ñÄ„Ö§ ‚ñÄ‚ñÄ‚ñÄ‚ñÄ„Ö§„Ö§ ‚ñÄ„Ö§„Ö§ „Ö§ ‚ñÄ‚ñÄ‚ñÄ‚ñÄ„Ö§ ‚ñà‚ñÄ‚ñÄ „ÄÄ „Ö§„Ö§„Ö§„Ö§„Ö§„Ö§‚ñ