an hour early, gets drunk on two bottles of light beer, throws up all over itself and has already passed out on the couch by the time the other guests arrive to draw dongs all over its face in sharpie markers. Avoid.", "appid": "356570", "steamid": "profiles/76561198002719210", "voted_up": false, "votes_up": 0, "votes_funny": 0, "early_access": false, "tstamp_created": 1472817600.0} {"text": "This protagonist ruins the Metro experience because of one single reason: he doesn‚Äôt speak or to be honest he does, but only in the loading screen and he has a really good voice actor. The characters around Artyom ask him questions and they answer to their own questions while he doesn‚Äôt have any reaction whatsoever. It's a shame because you can feel the sentiment between Artyom and Anna thanks to a few animations but it could have been much better. That excuse that some say ‚Äúit‚Äôs the whole silent protagonist thing where you are the real protagonist so it‚Äôs your voice that matters‚Äù doesn‚Äôt work a bit! The game is not designed to be like that but on the contrary people ask and speak continuously to Artyom and he just stands there mute and unemotional even when bad and important things happen. The best parts of the game are the ones with a lot of characters in one room because there you can try very hard to believe (hardly) this protagonist isn‚Äôt very talkative. I swear you can try and give all your best to roleplay emotions and a voice but everything is wrong because the reactions are so weird and the game is built around a protagonist that should speak more than anybody: a true leader. They're not amazing but I enjoyed them both (the first one is very good but very short, the second one is mediocre for its price but fun) and plus I felt much more empathy with the 2 protagonists since they actually use their voices. I wish the creator of Metro books would say something (and devs do something in eventual sequels) about the completely unjustified mute and unemotiona